					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I didn't even bring up the fact that not all games are JAMMA either.  *chuckle*  For example, Capcom's Trojan isn't. If used in a non-Trojan cabinet, you end up having to build JAMMA adapters, blah blah.  My point is that arcades are generally &quot;unique&quot; on a per-game basis, barring some exclusions, and they *aren't* cheap (they weren't then, nor are they now.  They were semi-affordable in the very late 90s/early 2000s, but that has changed (for the worse) due to collectors and hoarders).  The number of &quot;unique&quot; aspects to each game vary across the board (ex. PCB pinout, unique joystick or control panels, vector vs. CRT, and in some cases, even unique voltages (this is actually rare, but when it does happen, it's a nightmare.  There are some games which used JAMMA but with voltages rather than common -12V +5V -5V combo, so if you ended up throwing them on a common PSU, you'd potentially blow stuff up or have a non-functional game).  That's all I have to say on the matter.  You can read my blog sometime for stories/tales of why arcade stuff is a bloody nightmare.</div>

